<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 14 — Probability
  First draft for Part IV. Drafted in the Chapter 1 style:
    - chapter opener as a short multi-paragraph <introduction>
    - sections decomposed into named <paragraphs> subsections
    - <definition> callouts for technical vocabulary
    - <example> callouts for worked cases
    - <exploration> field exercise at the end of each section
    - "Where we're headed" subsection at the end of each section
    - <conclusion> Chapter Summary + Key Terms + end-of-chapter <exercises>

  Style conventions (carried over from Ch. 1):
    <term> = first introduction of a technical term (italic + indexed)
    <em>   = emphasis only, used sparingly
    italics for word-mention vs. term-introduction:
      mention only       → <em>probability</em>
      term-introduction  → <q><term>independent</term></q>

  Notes for review:
    - Knachel is the closest open-textbook neighbor; per D-031 we may adapt
      with attribution and corrections, but examples and prose here are
      drafted fresh. Known Knachel errors in the probability chapter (the
      base-rate worked example in particular) are deliberately avoided.
    - This chapter develops Bayes' theorem in §14.5, restricted to the
      two-hypothesis case (H and ~H). Multi-hypothesis Bayes is left to
      adopters who want to extend the chapter.
    - Notation: P(A), P(~A), P(A or B), P(A and B), P(A | B). The tilde
      `~` is the same tilde the book uses for negation in sentential
      logic; "and" and "or" are kept in English for events because they
      are the same conceptual connectives students met in Part III.
      "Complement" is the same notion that did the work in obversion
      and contraposition in Chapters 6 and 7.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-probability">

  <title>Probability</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-probability-intro">
    <p>
      Chapter 13 introduced inductive reasoning and asked: when premises
      do not guarantee a conclusion, how much do they support it?
      <q>Strong</q> and <q>weak</q> got us started. They are useful labels.
      But they are coarse. A weather forecast that says <q>likely rain</q>
      gives a verbal verdict; one that says <q>eighty percent chance
      of rain</q> gives a number.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter is about the numbers. <term>Probability</term> is the
      branch of reasoning that takes the rough vocabulary of likelihood
      and tightens it. Instead of saying <q>that's probably true,</q> we
      try to say how probable. Instead of saying <q>this evidence helps,</q>
      we try to say how much, and how it should change our confidence.
    </p>
    <p>
      A small warning before we start. People sometimes hear
      <em>probability</em> and brace for a wall of formulas. This
      chapter uses formulas as tools for careful thinking. Most
      everyday probability mistakes are mistakes about the question,
      the evidence, or the dependence relation. Get those right and
      the arithmetic mostly takes care of itself.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-from-likely-to-number">
    <title>From <q>How Likely?</q> to a Number</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Inductive reasoning is comfortable saying that one conclusion is
        more reasonable than another. Probability says how much more.
        That move — from comparison to quantity — is the central move of
        this chapter, and like most central moves, it sounds easier than
        it is.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-probability-as-bookkeeping">
      <title>Probability as bookkeeping</title>
      <p>
        Think of probability as a kind of bookkeeping for uncertainty.
        You start with a question — <em>will the bus be on time?</em>,
        <em>does this patient have strep?</em>, <em>will the next coin
        flip land heads?</em> — and you try to put a number on it that
        expresses how confident you should be in each possible answer,
        given what you know.
      </p>
      <p>
        The number lives between 0 and 1. A probability of 0 means the
        outcome is impossible given what you know. A probability of 1
        means it is certain. Everything else is in the middle, with
        bigger numbers meaning <q>more confident</q> and smaller numbers
        meaning <q>less confident.</q> A probability of 0.5 means
        you are equally pulled in either direction; a probability of
        0.9 means you would be a little surprised if the outcome did not
        happen; a probability of 0.01 means you would be very surprised
        if it did.
      </p>
      <p>
        Probabilities are sometimes written as percentages — <q>there is
        an 80 percent chance of rain</q> instead of <q>the probability
        is 0.8.</q> Sometimes they are written as odds — <q>three to
        one against.</q> The percentage form and the decimal form mean
        the same thing; you just slide the decimal point. The odds form
        means almost the same thing, with a different bit of arithmetic
        relating them. We will mostly use decimals in this book, with
        percentages now and then where they sound more natural.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-first-definition">
      <title>A first definition</title>
      <p>
        Here is a working definition. It is deliberately a little fuzzy.
        The next section sharpens it by introducing the three main ways
        people have tried to say what probability really <em>is</em>.
        For now we just want the working concept.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-probability">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>probability</term> is a number between 0 and 1 that
            represents how likely some outcome is. A probability of 0
            means the outcome will not happen. A probability of 1 means
            it will. Probabilities between 0 and 1 represent
            intermediate degrees of likelihood.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Two pieces of vocabulary that go with the definition.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-outcome-event">
        <statement>
          <p>
            An <term>outcome</term> is a possible specific result of
            some situation under consideration — a particular coin
            landing heads, a particular patient testing positive, a
            particular die showing 4.
          </p>
          <p>
            An <term>event</term> is a set of outcomes we care about
            together — <q>rolling an even number,</q> <q>drawing a heart
            or a spade,</q> <q>the bus being more than five minutes
            late.</q> When we write P(<em>E</em>) for an event, we mean
            the probability that one of the outcomes in <em>E</em>
            actually occurs.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Some textbooks distinguish carefully between outcomes and
        events. We will use whichever word is more natural for the
        example at hand. The important thing is to keep straight what
        the probability is <em>of</em>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-first-examples">
      <title>A few quick examples</title>
      <p>
        Some warmups, to make sure the bookkeeping feels concrete.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch14-coin">
        <title>A fair coin</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A fair coin has two possible outcomes when flipped: heads
            or tails. Each has probability 0.5. P(heads) = 0.5;
            P(tails) = 0.5. The two probabilities add to 1, because one
            of the two outcomes has to happen.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch14-die">
        <title>A fair six-sided die</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A fair six-sided die has six possible outcomes, each with
            probability 1/6. The probability of rolling an even number
            is the probability that the outcome is in the set
            {2, 4, 6}, which is 3/6, or 0.5.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch14-weather">
        <title>A weather forecast</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The forecast says <q>70 percent chance of rain tomorrow.</q>
            That number is a probability: P(rain tomorrow) = 0.7.
            The forecast still leaves a 30 percent chance of a dry day.
            One dry day does not discredit the technique or forecaster.
            A forecaster who says <q>70 percent</q> on a thousand
            similar days, and who is right roughly 700 of them, is
            doing the job well.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Two things to notice across these examples. First, the
        probability is always <em>relative to the situation under
        consideration</em>. We are not asking the probability of rain
        in general; we are asking the probability of rain tomorrow in
        this place given the current forecast. Second, the probability
        is always <em>relative to what you know</em>. If you had a
        magical certainty about tomorrow's weather, the probability
        would collapse to 0 or 1. The whole subject lives in the gap
        between guaranteed and unknown.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-probability-not-frequency">
      <title>Probability is not the same as frequency</title>
      <p>
        A common early instinct is to say: a probability just <em>is</em>
        how often something happens. If a coin lands heads about half
        the time, the probability of heads is 0.5; if it lands heads
        every time, the probability is 1.
      </p>
      <p>
        Frequency cannot define every probability we care about. Many
        probability claims concern cases we cannot repeat: a defendant's
        guilt, a single election, a particular diagnosis. The relationship
        between probability and frequency is real, but limited. We will
        spend the next section getting it right.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-14-1">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        We have the working concept. A probability is a number between
        0 and 1 that measures how likely an outcome is, relative to a
        situation and to what we know. The next section asks what kind
        of thing that number actually represents — long-run frequency,
        a feature of the setup, a degree of personal confidence, or
        some combination. Different answers to that question have
        different consequences for how we apply probability to real
        problems.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-14-1-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Estimate some probabilities</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write down your best estimate of the probability of each of
          the following. Use a decimal between 0 and 1. Then, for each
          one, write a sentence describing what kind of information
          would make you revise the estimate up or down.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>The next student who walks into your next class is wearing headphones.</p></li>
          <li><p>It will rain at some point in Fredericksburg tomorrow.</p></li>
          <li><p>Your phone battery makes it to the end of the day without recharging.</p></li>
          <li><p>The dining hall has run out of the entrée you wanted by the time you get there.</p></li>
          <li><p>A randomly chosen UMW student is a philosophy major.</p></li>
          <li><p>A randomly chosen UMW student has taken at least one philosophy course.</p></li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Notice how different the last two feel even though the
          sentences look almost identical. We will come back to that
          contrast when we talk about base rates.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-three-interpretations">
    <title>Three Ways to Think About Probability</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Probability is one of those rare topics where the mathematics
        is more settled than the philosophy. People have argued for
        centuries about what a probability <em>is</em> — what real-world
        thing the number is measuring. Three answers have stuck around
        long enough to be worth knowing. Each one captures something
        important. Each one runs into trouble at the edges. Most
        working scientists, statisticians, and philosophers use a mix.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-classical">
      <title>The classical interpretation</title>
      <p>
        The oldest answer comes from games of chance. If a situation
        has a finite number of equally likely outcomes, then the
        probability of an event is just the fraction of outcomes that
        count as that event.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-classical">
        <statement>
          <p>
            On the <term>classical interpretation</term>, the
            probability of an event is the number of outcomes favorable
            to the event divided by the total number of equally likely
            outcomes.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        The classical interpretation explains why a fair die has
        P(roll a 3) = 1/6 and why a randomly drawn card has
        P(heart) = 13/52 = 1/4. It works beautifully when the
        equally-likely outcomes are obvious — coins, dice, cards, balls
        in urns. It struggles once the outcomes get messy. What are
        the equally likely outcomes for <q>will it rain tomorrow</q>?
        You can imagine ways to force such cases into the classical
        form, but the forcing usually feels artificial. The classical
        interpretation is built around symmetry, and many real-world
        cases lack that symmetry.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-frequentist">
      <title>The frequentist interpretation</title>
      <p>
        The second answer fixes the symmetry problem by replacing it
        with repetition. Probability, on this view, is the long-run
        relative frequency of an event in a large number of similar
        trials.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-frequentist">
        <statement>
          <p>
            On the <term>frequentist interpretation</term>, the
            probability of an event is the proportion of times the
            event would occur in a long run of repeated trials of the
            same kind.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Toss a fair coin a thousand times and you expect about 500
        heads; toss it ten thousand times and the proportion gets
        closer to one-half. The frequentist says: <em>that</em> is
        what P(heads) = 0.5 means. It is a fact about the long run.
        This is the dominant interpretation in classical statistics,
        which we will use in later chapters of this part of the book.
      </p>
      <p>
        Its weakness is the single case. A frequentist has trouble
        saying what it means for <em>this</em> coin flip to have
        probability 0.5, or for <em>this</em> patient to have a 60
        percent chance of strep. The long run is somewhere out beyond
        the case in front of us. We often want to reason about the
        case in front of us.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-subjective">
      <title>The subjective (Bayesian) interpretation</title>
      <p>
        The third answer says: a probability is a degree of belief.
        It measures how confident a particular reasoner is, given the
        information they have, that some claim is true. It is in this
        sense personal — different reasoners with different information
        can rationally assign different probabilities to the same
        claim. The personal element is still constrained: subjective
        probabilities must obey rules of coherence, including all the
        basic rules we will spell out in the next section.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-subjective">
        <statement>
          <p>
            On the <term>subjective</term> or <term>Bayesian
            interpretation</term>, the probability of a claim is the
            degree of belief that a rational reasoner has in the claim,
            given their evidence. Probabilities are revised as new
            evidence comes in.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        The subjective interpretation is the natural home for the
        single case. <q>What's the probability that this defendant is
        guilty, given the evidence?</q> is a perfectly reasonable
        question for a Bayesian. So is <q>how confident should I be in
        this diagnosis, given what I have seen so far?</q> Bayesians
        also have a clean story about updating: when new evidence
        arrives, your probabilities should change in a specific way
        that we will introduce when we get to Bayes' theorem later in
        this chapter.
      </p>
      <p>
        Its weakness is that it leans on the word <em>rational</em>.
        Two careful reasoners can start from different priors and end
        up with different posterior probabilities even after seeing
        the same evidence. Bayesians have answers to this — over enough
        evidence, the priors get washed out, and coherence rules out
        many obviously crazy assignments — but the residual
        subjectivity worries some critics.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-why-three">
      <title>Why three interpretations matters in practice</title>
      <p>
        For most of this book, the three interpretations agree on the
        math. The basic rules we are about to state hold on all three
        views. They matter because each one pushes you toward
        different examples and different blind spots, and careful
        reasoners flex between them depending on the case. When we
        are doing sampling-based statistics in later chapters, we
        will lean frequentist. When we are reasoning about diagnosis,
        courtroom evidence, and other one-off cases, we will lean
        Bayesian. When we are working with idealized examples — coins,
        dice, urns — we will lean classical. Matching the tool to the
        problem is not cheating; it is the point.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-14-2">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        All three interpretations agree on the basic rules of
        probability. Those rules are the next section. They are short.
        They are also the source of nearly every probability mistake
        you will ever see, because applying them well requires reading
        a situation carefully — which means going slowly even though
        the formulas look easy.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-14-2-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Match the interpretation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For each of the following probability statements, which
          interpretation (classical, frequentist, or subjective) sits
          most naturally behind it? Some cases are mixed. Where they
          are mixed, say so and explain why.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p><q>The probability of drawing the ace of spades from a fair deck is 1/52.</q></p></li>
          <li><p><q>Based on the past ten years of campus weather data, the probability of snow on Move-In Day is about 0.02.</q></p></li>
          <li><p><q>Given the evidence so far, I'd say there's about a 70 percent chance the suspect was lying.</q></p></li>
          <li><p><q>In a long sequence of flips of this slightly bent coin, heads come up about 53 percent of the time.</q></p></li>
          <li><p><q>I'm 90 percent sure I left my keys in the car.</q></p></li>
          <li><p><q>The probability that a randomly selected first-year student is enrolled in PHIL 151B this semester is 6 percent.</q></p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-probability-rules">
    <title>The Basic Rules</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The rules of probability are deceptively few. You can write
        them down on a notecard. The trick is that almost every
        probability mistake people make is a careless application of
        one of these rules, usually because the situation was harder
        to read than it looked.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-1-range">
      <title>Probabilities sit between 0 and 1</title>
      <p>
        Every probability is at least 0 and at most 1. There is no
        such thing as a probability of <m>-0.2</m> or 1.4 or 110
        percent. (Sportscasters who say <q>he gave 110 percent</q> are
        not making a probability claim. They are abusing arithmetic on
        purpose.)
      </p>
      <p>
        A probability of 0 means the event will definitely not happen,
        given what you know. A probability of 1 means it will
        definitely happen. Anything in between is a degree of
        confidence.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-2-total">
      <title>Something always happens: the total is 1</title>
      <p>
        If you list all the possible outcomes of a situation, with no
        overlaps and nothing left out, their probabilities have to add
        to exactly 1. Something is going to happen, even if you don't
        know which.
      </p>
      <p>
        For a fair coin, P(heads) + P(tails) = 0.5 + 0.5 = 1. For a
        fair six-sided die, the six outcomes each have probability
        1/6, and 6 × 1/6 = 1. For tomorrow's weather, P(rain) +
        P(no rain) = 1, because one of those two has to be the case.
      </p>
      <p>
        The point seems obvious until you start using it. We rely on
        it constantly, especially in its next form.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-complement">
      <title>The complement rule</title>
      <p>
        The probability that an event does <em>not</em> happen is one
        minus the probability that it does. This is the
        <term>complement rule</term>. We write the complement of
        <em>A</em> as <m>{\sim}A</m>, using the same tilde the book
        uses for negation in sentential logic. This is also the same
        notion of complement that did the work in obversion and
        contraposition in Chapters 6 and 7: the complement of a class
        or event is everything not in it.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-complement-rule">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any event <em>A</em>:
            <m>P({\sim}A) = 1 - P(A).</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        If the probability of rain tomorrow is 0.7, the probability of
        no rain is 0.3. If the probability of drawing a heart from a
        standard deck is 0.25, the probability of drawing something
        that is not a heart is 0.75.
      </p>
      <p>
        The complement rule is more useful than it looks. Sometimes
        the probability of an event is much harder to compute than the
        probability of its complement. <q>At least one</q> problems
        are the classic case. The probability of rolling at least one
        6 in four rolls of a fair die is fiddly to compute directly,
        because <q>at least one 6</q> includes <em>exactly one</em>,
        <em>exactly two</em>, <em>exactly three</em>, and
        <em>exactly four</em>. The probability of the complement —
        <em>no 6 at all</em> — is much easier: it's just the
        probability that each of the four rolls fails to show a 6,
        multiplied together. Then we subtract from 1.
      </p>
      <p>
        Whenever a probability problem starts with <q>at least one,</q>
        check whether the complement is easier.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-addition-rule">
      <title>Mutually exclusive events: the addition rule</title>
      <p>
        Two events are <term>mutually exclusive</term> when they
        cannot both happen at the same time. A single coin flip cannot
        land both heads and tails. A single die roll cannot show both
        2 and 5. A single drawn card cannot be both a heart and a
        spade.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-mutually-exclusive">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two events are <term>mutually exclusive</term> when they
            cannot both occur on the same trial.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        When events are mutually exclusive, the probability that one
        <em>or</em> the other happens is the sum of their individual
        probabilities.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-addition-rule-disjoint">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <term>Addition rule (mutually exclusive case).</term>
            If <em>A</em> and <em>B</em> are mutually exclusive, then
            <m>P(A \text{ or } B) = P(A) + P(B).</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch14-die-or">
        <title>Rolling a 1 or a 6</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            On a single roll of a fair six-sided die, the events
            <q>rolls a 1</q> and <q>rolls a 6</q> are mutually
            exclusive. So
            P(rolls a 1 or a 6) = P(rolls a 1) + P(rolls a 6)
            = 1/6 + 1/6 = 2/6 = 1/3.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-general-addition-rule">
      <title>When events overlap: the general addition rule</title>
      <p>
        When events overlap, simply adding their probabilities
        double-counts the overlap. Drawing a heart and drawing a face
        card overlap in three cards: the jack, queen, and king of
        hearts. If we add P(heart) and P(face card) without adjustment,
        we count those three cards twice.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-general-addition-rule">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <term>General addition rule.</term> For any two events
            <em>A</em> and <em>B</em>,
            <m>P(A \text{ or } B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \text{ and } B).</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch14-heart-or-face">
        <title>A heart or a face card</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            From a standard 52-card deck:
            P(heart) = 13/52, P(face card) = 12/52, and
            P(heart and face card) = 3/52 (the J, Q, K of hearts).
          </p>
          <p>
            By the general addition rule:
            P(heart or face card) = 13/52 + 12/52 − 3/52 = 22/52, or
            roughly 0.42.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        When events are mutually exclusive, the
        P(A and B) term in the general rule is 0, and the rule
        collapses to the simpler version. The two addition rules are
        one idea written in two useful forms.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-14-3">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        We can now compute the probability of a single event, the
        probability that an event does <em>not</em> happen, and the
        probability that one event or another happens. The remaining
        major case is the probability that two events both happen.
        That brings us to <term>conditional probability</term>, the
        single most powerful — and most error-prone — idea in
        elementary probability.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-conditional-independence">
    <title>Conditional Probability and Independence</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        So far we have treated probabilities as fixed numbers attached
        to events. In practice, probabilities change as new information
        comes in. <q>The probability of rain</q> is one number before
        you check the radar and another after. <q>The probability the
        suspect is guilty</q> shifts as evidence comes in. The tool
        that makes those shifts precise is conditional probability.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-conditional-probability">
      <title>Probability, given something</title>
      <p>
        A <term>conditional probability</term> is the probability of
        one event given that another event has occurred. We write it
        with a vertical bar: P(<em>A</em> | <em>B</em>), read
        <q>the probability of A given B.</q>
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-conditional-probability">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>conditional probability</term> of <em>A</em>
            given <em>B</em>, written
            P(<em>A</em> | <em>B</em>), is the probability that
            <em>A</em> occurs assuming that <em>B</em> has occurred.
            Provided P(<em>B</em>) is greater than 0,
            <m>P(A \mid B) = \dfrac{P(A \text{ and } B)}{P(B)}.</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        The formula has an intuitive picture behind it. Imagine all
        the ways the situation could turn out, weighted by their
        probabilities. Conditioning on <em>B</em> means restricting
        attention to the slice of possibilities in which <em>B</em>
        happens. Within that slice, what fraction also have <em>A</em>?
        That fraction is P(<em>A</em> | <em>B</em>).
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch14-die-conditional">
        <title>A die, conditional on an even roll</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Roll a fair six-sided die once. The unconditional
            probability of rolling a 4 is 1/6. The conditional
            probability of rolling a 4 given that the roll is even is
            1/3, because among the three even outcomes (2, 4, 6),
            exactly one is a 4.
          </p>
          <p>
            Plug into the definition:
            P(4 and even) = P(4) = 1/6.
            P(even) = 1/2.
            P(4 | even) = (1/6) / (1/2) = 1/3.
            The picture and the formula agree.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-multiplication-rule">
      <title>The multiplication rule</title>
      <p>
        Rearranging the conditional probability formula gives a
        formula for the probability of both events happening:
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-multiplication-rule">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <term>Multiplication rule.</term> For any two events
            <em>A</em> and <em>B</em>,
            <m>P(A \text{ and } B) = P(A \mid B) \cdot P(B) = P(B \mid A) \cdot P(A).</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        In English: the probability that two events both happen is the
        probability of one, times the probability of the other given
        the first. You can pick whichever order of conditioning is
        easier to think about. The result is the same.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch14-two-cards">
        <title>Drawing two hearts without replacement</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Draw two cards from a standard 52-card deck without
            putting the first back. What is the probability that both
            are hearts?
          </p>
          <p>
            P(first card is a heart) = 13/52.
            Given that the first card is a heart, there are 12 hearts
            left in the remaining 51 cards, so
            P(second card is a heart | first card is a heart) = 12/51.
          </p>
          <p>
            By the multiplication rule:
            P(both hearts) = (13/52) × (12/51) = 156/2652
            approximately 0.059, or about 6 percent.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-independence">
      <title>Independence</title>
      <p>
        Two events are <term>independent</term> when knowing that one
        happened does not change the probability of the other.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-independence">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two events <em>A</em> and <em>B</em> are
            <term>independent</term> when
            <m>P(A \mid B) = P(A),</m>
            or equivalently
            <m>P(A \text{ and } B) = P(A) \cdot P(B).</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Independent events are the easiest case of the multiplication
        rule. If two flips of a fair coin are independent, the
        probability that both come up heads is 0.5 × 0.5 = 0.25. If
        five rolls of a fair die are independent, the probability of
        rolling a 6 every time is (1/6)<m>{}^5</m>, about 0.00013.
      </p>
      <p>
        Independence is a strong claim. Real-world events that look
        independent often share a common cause. Two students in the same
        dorm catching a cold in the same week may both trace back to the
        dorm. Two missed questions on the same exam may both trace back
        to preparation.
      </p>
      <p>
        A clean way to spot a dependence problem: ask whether the
        probability of one event would change if you learned the other
        happened. If yes, the events are dependent. If no, they are
        independent.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-three-classic-mistakes">
      <title>Three classic mistakes</title>
      <p>
        Conditional probability is fertile ground for mistakes. Three
        come up so often that they have names.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>gambler's fallacy</term> treats independent trials
        as if previous outcomes change the probability of future
        ones. <q>The roulette wheel has come up red five times in a
        row, so black is due.</q> The wheel has no memory. If it is
        fair, each spin is independent, and the probability of red on
        the next spin remains 18/38. Previous spins provide no evidence
        about the current spin.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>conjunction fallacy</term> treats the probability
        of two events both happening as if it could be greater than
        the probability of just one of them. It cannot.
        <m>P(A \text{ and } B) \leq P(A)</m>, always — adding
        a second requirement can only narrow the set of
        possibilities. Yet people routinely rate detailed scenarios
        as more probable than matching simpler ones, because the
        details make the scenario feel more plausible. The classic
        demonstration is Tversky and Kahneman's <q>Linda</q> problem.
        Subjects read a short description of Linda — a thoughtful,
        outspoken woman who majored in philosophy in college and was
        concerned with issues of social justice — and are asked which
        is more probable: (a) Linda is a bank teller, or (b) Linda is
        a bank teller and is active in the feminist movement. Most
        pick (b). But the set of bank-teller feminists is a subset of
        the set of bank tellers, so (b) cannot be more probable than
        (a); the conjunction always has probability less than or
        equal to either conjunct. Plausibility and probability are
        not the same. (See Tversky and Kahneman, <q>Extensional
        Versus Intuitive Reasoning: The Conjunction Fallacy in
        Probability Judgment,</q> <em>Psychological Review</em> 90
        (1983).)
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>prosecutor's fallacy</term> confuses
        P(<em>A</em> | <em>B</em>) with P(<em>B</em> | <em>A</em>).
        Conditional probabilities are directional, and the two
        directions can be wildly different numbers. Almost every dog
        is a mammal: P(mammal | dog) is essentially 1. Most mammals
        are not dogs: P(dog | mammal) is much smaller. Same two
        categories, two very different conditional probabilities.
        Mixing up the direction is what gives the prosecutor's
        fallacy its name: the move from <q>the probability of this
        evidence given that the defendant is innocent is small</q>
        to <q>the probability that the defendant is innocent given
        this evidence is small.</q> Those are different sentences
        and different numbers. Confusing them has put innocent
        people in prison.
      </p>
      <p>
        All three fallacies have the same shape. They mistake the
        psychological pull of a pattern, a story, or a number for
        the structural constraints of probability. Probabilities
        care about counts, not narratives. The next section gives us
        the tool — Bayes' theorem — that makes the
        prosecutor's-fallacy mistake easy to diagnose by showing
        exactly how the two directions of a conditional are related.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-14-4">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        Conditional probability gives us a way to ask: given the
        evidence, how likely is the claim? That is the question we
        ask all the time. The next section turns the rules for
        conditional probability into Bayes' theorem — a formula for
        moving from a prior probability to a posterior probability
        when new evidence arrives.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-14-4-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Conditional and joint</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A campus dining survey of 200 students records two things
          for each student: whether they ate breakfast that day, and
          whether they used the on-campus dining hall (as opposed to
          off-campus food or no breakfast at all).
        </p>
        <p>
          The results:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>120 students ate breakfast; 80 did not.</p></li>
          <li><p>Of the 120 who ate breakfast, 90 used the dining hall.</p></li>
          <li><p>Of the 80 who did not eat breakfast, 20 still used the dining hall for coffee or a snack.</p></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          For a randomly chosen student in the survey, compute:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>P(ate breakfast).</p></li>
          <li><p>P(used the dining hall).</p></li>
          <li><p>P(used the dining hall and ate breakfast).</p></li>
          <li><p>P(used the dining hall | ate breakfast).</p></li>
          <li><p>P(ate breakfast | used the dining hall).</p></li>
          <li><p>Are the events <q>ate breakfast</q> and <q>used the dining hall</q> independent? Defend your answer using the numbers.</p></li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Pay attention to the difference between items 4 and 5. Same
          two events, opposite directions.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-bayes">
    <title>Bayes' Theorem</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Probabilities change when evidence arrives. Conditional
        probability gave us the language to say so: P(H | E) is the
        probability of a hypothesis <em>H</em> given some evidence
        <em>E</em>. What we have not yet done is solve for it. In
        most real situations, what we know is P(E | H) — how likely
        the evidence would be if the hypothesis were true — and what
        we want is P(H | E), how confident the evidence should make
        us in the hypothesis. <term>Bayes' theorem</term> turns the
        first into the second.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-prior-posterior">
      <title>Prior and posterior</title>
      <p>
        Before evidence arrives, you have some probability for a
        hypothesis. Call that the <term>prior probability</term>.
        After you update on the evidence, you have a new
        probability. Call that the <term>posterior probability</term>.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-prior-posterior">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>prior probability</term> of a hypothesis is
            its probability before a given piece of evidence is
            taken into account. The <term>posterior probability</term>
            is its probability after the evidence is taken into
            account.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        We will work only with cases that have two competing
        hypotheses: <em>H</em> and its negation
        <m>{\sim}H</m>. Either the person has the disease or they
        do not. Either the package was stolen or it was not. Either
        the suspect was at the scene or they were not. Cases with
        three or more competing hypotheses use the same idea with
        more bookkeeping, but the two-hypothesis case is the right
        place to start, and it is the only case we will ask you to
        compute in this chapter.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-bayes-formula">
      <title>The formula</title>
      <p>
        Here is Bayes' theorem in the form you will actually use.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch14-bayes-theorem">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <term>Bayes' theorem (two-hypothesis case).</term> For a
            hypothesis <em>H</em> and evidence <em>E</em>, the
            posterior probability of <em>H</em> given <em>E</em> is
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>P(H \mid E) \;=\; \dfrac{P(E \mid H)\,P(H)}{P(E \mid H)\,P(H) \;+\; P(E \mid {\sim}H)\,P({\sim}H)}.</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Four ingredients go in:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>P(<em>H</em>), the prior probability of the hypothesis;</p></li>
        <li><p>P(<m>{\sim}H</m>) = 1 − P(<em>H</em>), the prior probability of its negation, by the complement rule;</p></li>
        <li><p>P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>), the probability of the evidence if the hypothesis is true;</p></li>
        <li><p>P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>), the probability of the evidence if the hypothesis is false.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        One thing comes out: P(<em>H</em> | <em>E</em>), the
        posterior probability — the answer we actually want.
      </p>
      <p>
        Where does the formula come from? Three short steps from
        rules we have already stated. First, by the definition of
        conditional probability,
        P(<em>H</em> | <em>E</em>) = P(<em>H</em> and <em>E</em>) /
        P(<em>E</em>). Second, by the multiplication rule, the
        numerator P(<em>H</em> and <em>E</em>) can also be written
        as P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) · P(<em>H</em>). Third, the
        denominator P(<em>E</em>) breaks into two mutually exclusive
        cases — either <em>E</em> happens together with <em>H</em>,
        or it happens together with <m>{\sim}H</m> — and by the
        multiplication rule applied to each:
        P(<em>E</em>) = P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) · P(<em>H</em>) +
        P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>) · P(<m>{\sim}H</m>).
        Substitute, and the formula above is what falls out.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-bayes-medical">
      <title>A worked example: the medical test</title>
      <p>
        Suppose a disease affects 1 person in 1,000. A test for the
        disease is 99 percent accurate in both directions: 99 percent
        of people who have the disease test positive, and 99 percent
        of people who do not have the disease test negative. Your
        test comes back positive. What is the probability that you
        actually have the disease?
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch14-bayes-medical">
        <title>Bayes' theorem applied to the medical test</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <em>H</em> = <q>has the disease</q> and <em>E</em> =
            <q>tests positive.</q> The four ingredients:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><p>P(<em>H</em>) = 0.001 (the base rate);</p></li>
            <li><p>P(<m>{\sim}H</m>) = 0.999;</p></li>
            <li><p>P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) = 0.99 (the true-positive rate);</p></li>
            <li><p>P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>) = 0.01 (the false-positive rate).</p></li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Plug into Bayes' theorem:
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>P(H \mid E) \;=\; \dfrac{(0.99)(0.001)}{(0.99)(0.001) + (0.01)(0.999)} \;=\; \dfrac{0.00099}{0.01098} \;\approx\; 0.090.</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            The answer is about 9 percent, even though the test is often
            described as <q>99 percent accurate.</q>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        There is a slower way to see the same number by counting.
        Imagine 10,000 randomly chosen people:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>About 10 have the disease (the base rate is 1 in 1,000). The test correctly flags about all 10. These are the <term>true positives</term>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The other 9,990 do not have the disease. The test wrongly flags about 100 of them. These are the <term>false positives</term>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Total positive results: about 110. Of those, only about 10 actually have the disease.</p></li>
        <li><p>So P(<em>H</em> | <em>E</em>) is approximately 10 / 110, or approximately 0.09.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Same answer. The count approach is more intuitive; the
        formula is more general. They are the same arithmetic in two
        different outfits, and it is worth doing both at least once
        so the formula stops feeling magical.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-bayes-priors-matter">
      <title>The prior makes the answer</title>
      <p>
        Re-run the medical-test example with a different prior to
        see how much the answer depends on the base rate. Hold the
        test accuracy fixed at P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) = 0.99 and
        P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>) = 0.01.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>If P(<em>H</em>) = 0.001 (rare disease in the general population), the posterior is about 9 percent.</p></li>
        <li><p>If P(<em>H</em>) = 0.01 (less rare), the posterior is about 50 percent.</p></li>
        <li><p>If P(<em>H</em>) = 0.10 (the patient is already in a high-risk group), the posterior is about 92 percent.</p></li>
        <li><p>If P(<em>H</em>) = 0.50 (no reason to think the patient is more or less at risk than chance), the posterior is 99 percent.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Same test, same accuracy, wildly different posteriors. The
        reason is structural: the numerator of Bayes' theorem
        multiplies the prior P(<em>H</em>) by the likelihood
        P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>). When the prior is tiny, even a
        strong likelihood cannot lift the posterior very far,
        because the denominator is dominated by the false-positive
        term P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>) · P(<m>{\sim}H</m>).
        When the prior is moderate, the same likelihood lifts the
        posterior close to certainty.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the formal version of <term>base-rate neglect</term>.
        People who ignore the prior tend to confuse
        P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) — what they read off the test's
        accuracy claim — with P(<em>H</em> | <em>E</em>) — the
        answer they actually want. Bayes' theorem is the bookkeeping
        that prevents the confusion, and it makes the prosecutor's
        fallacy from §14.4 easy to diagnose: the two directions are
        equal only when the priors balance the likelihoods just
        right, which they almost never do.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-14-5">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        We now have everything we need to talk quantitatively about
        uncertainty: a working concept of probability, three
        interpretations behind it, the basic rules, conditional
        probability, independence, and Bayes' theorem for updating
        in the two-hypothesis case. The next chapter shifts from
        individual probabilities to whole collections of data —
        averages, spreads, and the shapes of distributions — which
        is the descriptive half of statistical reasoning. The
        chapter after that puts probability and description back
        together as statistical <em>inference</em>: using data from
        a sample to learn about a population we cannot observe
        directly.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-14-5-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Apply Bayes' theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A campus security camera flags potential package thefts.
          From a year of footage, the security office estimates:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>P(<em>H</em>) = 0.01: of all packages delivered, 1 percent are actually stolen (<em>H</em> = <q>this package was stolen</q>).</p></li>
          <li><p>P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) = 0.95: when a package is in fact stolen, the camera flags the incident 95 percent of the time (<em>E</em> = <q>the camera flagged this delivery</q>).</p></li>
          <li><p>P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>) = 0.04: when a package is not stolen, the camera flags it anyway about 4 percent of the time, because of misreads.</p></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Plug into Bayes' theorem and compute
          P(<em>H</em> | <em>E</em>): given that the camera flagged
          a delivery, what is the probability that the package was
          actually stolen? Then, in one sentence, describe what
          changes if the actual theft rate were instead 10 percent
          rather than 1 percent.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch14">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced probability as a precise vocabulary for
      degrees of likelihood and changing confidence. The core ideas,
      section by section:
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>From <q>How Likely?</q> to a Number (§14.1).</alert> A
      probability is a number between 0 and 1 that represents how
      likely an outcome is, given a situation and what we know about
      it. Probabilities can be written as decimals, percentages, or
      odds; they all encode the same underlying number. Long-run
      frequency is one important way to interpret probability,
      especially across repeated trials.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Three Ways to Think About Probability (§14.2).</alert>
      The <em>classical</em> interpretation treats probability as the
      ratio of favorable outcomes to equally likely outcomes. The
      <em>frequentist</em> interpretation treats probability as the
      long-run proportion in a sequence of similar trials. The
      <em>subjective</em> or <em>Bayesian</em> interpretation treats
      probability as a rational degree of belief, constrained by
      coherence and revisable in light of evidence. All three agree
      on the basic rules; they disagree about what the rules are
      describing. Careful reasoners flex between interpretations
      depending on the case.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>The Basic Rules (§14.3).</alert> Every probability is
      between 0 and 1. The probabilities of an exhaustive,
      non-overlapping set of outcomes add to 1. The complement rule
      says P(not A) = 1 − P(A). The addition rule for mutually
      exclusive events says P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B). The general
      addition rule says P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A and B),
      collapsing to the mutually-exclusive case when the events do
      not overlap.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Conditional Probability and Independence (§14.4).</alert>
      The conditional probability P(A | B) is the probability of A
      given that B has occurred, equal to P(A and B) / P(B). The
      multiplication rule gives P(A and B) = P(A | B) · P(B). Two
      events are independent when conditioning on one does not change
      the probability of the other. Three frequent errors: the
      gambler's fallacy (treating independent events as
      dependent), the conjunction fallacy (treating P(A and B) as
      larger than P(A)), and confusion between P(A | B) and
      P(B | A), which is the structure of the prosecutor's fallacy.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Bayes' Theorem (§14.5).</alert> A probability before a
      piece of evidence is the <em>prior</em>; after the evidence,
      the <em>posterior</em>. In the two-hypothesis case (<em>H</em>
      and <m>{\sim}H</m>), Bayes' theorem computes the posterior from
      the prior and the likelihood of the evidence under each
      hypothesis:
      <m>P(H \mid E) = \dfrac{P(E \mid H)\,P(H)}{P(E \mid H)\,P(H) + P(E \mid {\sim}H)\,P({\sim}H)}.</m>
      The formula takes four numbers in — the prior P(<em>H</em>),
      its complement P(<m>{\sim}H</m>), and the two likelihoods
      P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) and P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>) —
      and returns one number out, the posterior P(<em>H</em> | <em>E</em>).
      The medical-test worked example shows the moral. A test that is
      99% accurate, applied to a disease with a base rate of 1 in
      1,000, raises the probability of the disease to only about 9%
      after a positive result. With a small prior, the false positives
      pulled from the many healthy people outnumber the true positives
      pulled from the few sick ones — even when the test is highly
      accurate, most of its positives are wrong. <em>Base-rate
      neglect</em> is the corresponding reasoning error: reading the
      test's accuracy off as if it were the answer, and leaving the
      prior P(<em>H</em>) out of the calculation entirely.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch14-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-addition-rule">
        <title>Addition rule</title>
        <p>For any two events, P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A and B). When A and B are mutually exclusive, the last term is 0 and the rule reduces to P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B). (§14.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-base-rate">
        <title>Base rate</title>
        <p>The unconditional probability of an outcome in the population under consideration. Updating without accounting for the base rate is <em>base-rate neglect</em>. (§14.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-bayes-theorem">
        <title>Bayes' theorem</title>
        <p>In the two-hypothesis case, the posterior probability of <em>H</em> given <em>E</em> is <m>P(H \mid E) = P(E \mid H)\,P(H) / \bigl[P(E \mid H)\,P(H) + P(E \mid {\sim}H)\,P({\sim}H)\bigr].</m> Used to update a prior probability in light of evidence. (§14.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-bayesian">
        <title>Bayesian (subjective) interpretation</title>
        <p>Interpretation of probability as a rational degree of belief, constrained by coherence and revised by new evidence. (§14.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-classical-interp">
        <title>Classical interpretation</title>
        <p>Interpretation of probability as the ratio of outcomes favorable to an event to the total number of equally likely outcomes. (§14.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-complement-rule">
        <title>Complement rule</title>
        <p>P(not A) = 1 − P(A). (§14.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-conditional-probability">
        <title>Conditional probability</title>
        <p>The probability of A given B, written P(A | B), equal to P(A and B) / P(B) when P(B) &gt; 0. (§14.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-conjunction-fallacy">
        <title>Conjunction fallacy</title>
        <p>The mistake of treating P(A and B) as greater than P(A) or P(B), often produced by mistaking plausibility for probability. (§14.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-event">
        <title>Event</title>
        <p>A set of outcomes treated together — the outcomes for which some condition is met. (§14.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-false-positive">
        <title>False positive</title>
        <p>A positive test result for a person or case that does not actually have the condition being tested for. (§14.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-frequentist-interp">
        <title>Frequentist interpretation</title>
        <p>Interpretation of probability as the long-run relative frequency of an event in a sequence of similar trials. (§14.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-gamblers-fallacy">
        <title>Gambler's fallacy</title>
        <p>The mistake of treating independent trials as if previous outcomes change the probability of future outcomes. (§14.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-independence">
        <title>Independence</title>
        <p>Two events are independent when P(A | B) = P(A), equivalently P(A and B) = P(A) · P(B). (§14.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-multiplication-rule">
        <title>Multiplication rule</title>
        <p>P(A and B) = P(A | B) · P(B) = P(B | A) · P(A). For independent events this simplifies to P(A and B) = P(A) · P(B). (§14.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-mutually-exclusive">
        <title>Mutually exclusive</title>
        <p>Two events are mutually exclusive when they cannot both occur on the same trial. (§14.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-outcome">
        <title>Outcome</title>
        <p>A specific possible result of a situation under consideration. (§14.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-posterior-probability">
        <title>Posterior probability</title>
        <p>The probability of a claim after a piece of evidence has been taken into account. (§14.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-prior-probability">
        <title>Prior probability</title>
        <p>The probability of a claim before a piece of evidence is taken into account. (§14.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-probability">
        <title>Probability</title>
        <p>A number between 0 and 1 that represents how likely an outcome is, relative to a situation and to what is known about it. (§14.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-prosecutors-fallacy">
        <title>Prosecutor's fallacy</title>
        <p>Confusing P(evidence | innocence) with P(innocence | evidence) — treating a small probability of the evidence under innocence as if it were a small probability of innocence given the evidence. (§14.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch14-true-positive">
        <title>True positive</title>
        <p>A positive test result for a person or case that actually has the condition being tested for. Compare with <em>false positive</em>. (§14.5)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch14">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch14-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Basic rules</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each problem, identify the rule(s) you need and compute
          the probability. Express answers as fractions or decimals.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>A fair coin is flipped. What is the probability that it lands tails?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>A fair six-sided die is rolled. What is the probability that it does <em>not</em> land on a 5?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>One card is drawn from a standard 52-card deck. What is the probability that the card is either a 2 or a 3?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>One card is drawn from a standard 52-card deck. What is the probability that the card is a face card or a club?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s01-05">
        <statement>
          <p>The probability that a randomly chosen UMW student has declared a major is 0.78. What is the probability that the student has not declared a major?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s01-06">
        <statement>
          <p>A spinner has four equally sized colored regions: red, blue, green, and yellow. What is the probability that the spinner lands on red or green?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch14-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Conditional probability</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each problem, compute the requested conditional or joint
          probability. Show the work, including which rule was used.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>A fair six-sided die is rolled. Given that the outcome is odd, what is the probability that the outcome is 3?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Two cards are drawn from a standard 52-card deck without replacement. What is the probability that both are aces?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <p>A bag holds 5 red marbles and 7 blue marbles. A marble is drawn at random and not replaced; then a second marble is drawn. What is the probability that the first is red and the second is blue?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s02-04">
        <statement>
          <p>A fair coin is flipped three times. What is the probability of getting heads all three times?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s02-05">
        <statement>
          <p>A fair coin is flipped three times. What is the probability of getting at least one tail? (Hint: consider the complement.)</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch14-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Independence</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each pair of events, decide whether they are plausibly
          independent. Defend your answer in a sentence.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <p>(A) The next flip of a fair coin lands heads. (B) The flip after that lands heads.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <p>(A) A randomly chosen UMW student is a first-year. (B) The same student lives in on-campus housing.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <p>(A) It rains in Fredericksburg tomorrow morning. (B) Class attendance in PHIL 151B is lower than usual tomorrow.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s03-04">
        <statement>
          <p>(A) A randomly chosen UMW student is a philosophy major. (B) The same student is enrolled in MATH 110.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s03-05">
        <statement>
          <p>(A) The first card drawn from a shuffled deck is a heart. (B) The second card drawn from the same deck, without replacement, is a heart.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch14-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Direction of conditioning</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each pair of probabilities, decide whether they are
          (almost certainly) close to each other or (likely) very
          different. Explain.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>P(left-handed | professional baseball pitcher) and P(professional baseball pitcher | left-handed).</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>P(wears glasses | UMW student) and P(UMW student | wears glasses).</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p>P(has a fever | has the flu) and P(has the flu | has a fever).</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <p>P(lottery ticket wins | the ticket was bought yesterday) and P(the ticket was bought yesterday | lottery ticket wins).</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch14-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Bayes' theorem and base rates</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each scenario, identify <em>H</em> and <em>E</em>. Where
          the four ingredients (P(<em>H</em>), P(<m>{\sim}H</m>),
          P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>), P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>))
          are all given, compute P(<em>H</em> | <em>E</em>) using
          Bayes' theorem; the 10,000-people count method gives the
          same answer if you prefer to start there. Where the base
          rate or false-positive rate is missing, say which number
          you would need and why. In every case use only two
          hypotheses: <em>H</em> and <m>{\sim}H</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s05-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A rare medical condition affects 1 in 500 people in a
            population. A screening test is 98 percent accurate in
            both directions (98 percent of people with the condition
            test positive; 98 percent of people without it test
            negative). Someone in this population tests positive.
            Roughly what is the probability that they actually have
            the condition?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s05-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A car alarm goes off about once a week in a parking lot
            with hundreds of cars. The alarm is loud and persuasive.
            A neighbor says, <q>The alarm sounds, so the car is
            probably being broken into.</q> Comment on the reasoning.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s05-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A study finds that 90 percent of people who fail a course
            in their first semester have study habits in the bottom
            quartile. A first-year student has study habits in the
            bottom quartile. They conclude that they will probably
            fail at least one course. Comment on the reasoning.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-s05-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A defendant matches a DNA profile that occurs in 1 in
            10,000 people. The prosecutor says, <q>The chance that an
            innocent person would match this profile is 1 in 10,000,
            so the chance that this defendant is innocent is 1 in
            10,000.</q> What is wrong with this argument?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch14-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This prompt extends Field Exercise 14-5.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find one news story, advertisement, public-health claim,
            or campus message from the last week that mentions a
            probability, a percentage, or a comparison of likelihoods.
            Reconstruct the claim in your own words. Identify the base
            rate it depends on (or notice if the base rate is missing).
            Then say whether you think the claim is using probability
            responsibly. Limit yourself to about 300 words.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
